      "blocks": {
        "faq-1": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Why did I develop food sensitivities after moving countries?",
            "answer": "<p>Your gut bacteria produce the enzymes that digest the foods your ancestors ate for generations. L. acidophilus produces lactase for dairy. L. plantarum produces the enzymes that break down legumes, onions, and garlic. When you adopt a Western diet that your ancestral microbiome wasn't evolved for, these specific bacterial populations deplete within one generation (documented by Vangay et al., 2018). The foods didn't become a problem. The bacteria that processed them disappeared.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-2": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How is Origin different from taking lactase or Beano pills?",
            "answer": "<p>Enzyme pills provide temporary external enzymes for that specific meal. You have to remember them, time them correctly, and take them indefinitely. Origin restores the bacterial populations that produce these enzymes naturally, continuously, from inside your gut. When L. acidophilus is re-established, your gut makes its own lactase. When L. plantarum is re-established, legumes and alliums process normally. The goal is to stop needing the pills — not to take them forever.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-3": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "How long until I can eat dairy and legumes normally again?",
            "answer": "<p>Most people notice the first improvements within 3-4 weeks. Dairy typically improves first, followed by legumes and alliums (onion, garlic). Full enzymatic restoration — where foods that previously caused severe reactions become completely tolerable — typically develops over 6-12 weeks as the bacterial populations stabilize and re-establish. Results depend on how depleted your microbiome is and how consistently you take Origin.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-4": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Is my lactose intolerance permanent?",
            "answer": "<p>For most people with acquired lactose intolerance — especially those who tolerated dairy in childhood or before immigrating — the intolerance is not genetic or permanent. It's functional: the bacteria that produce lactase have declined below the threshold needed for effective digestion. This is reversible when the bacterial populations are restored. Primary lactase deficiency (genetic, present from birth) is different — but even in those cases, restoring other aspects of microbiome function can reduce the severity of reactions.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq-5": {
          "type": "question",
          "settings": {
            "question": "Can I take Origin if I already have confirmed food allergies?",
            "answer": "<p>Food sensitivities (intolerances) and food allergies are different conditions. Food allergies involve an immune response to a specific protein — not a digestive enzyme deficiency. Origin addresses bacterial-enzyme-mediated intolerances, not IgE-mediated allergies. If you have confirmed allergies (anaphylaxis, hives, severe reactions), consult your physician before any changes to your diet or supplement routine. Origin is safe alongside most supplement and medication protocols, but your allergist should be involved in any dietary expansion.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
